\cf1\b Description\cf3\b0\par
The goal of this exercise is to achieve a high score by destroying Roids!\par
\par
You have been supplied with three ships. Each ship can rotate left and right and thrust in the direction it is pointed. Station keeping thrusters will slowly reduce its speed, eventually bringing it to a full stop.\par
\par
Each ship is equipped with a main gun that fires a bullet in the same direction the ship faces. The main gun has an unlimited supply of bullets but your ship's tracking computer will limit the number of bullets you can fire. The tracking computer uses the bullet self-destruct mechanism to limit their range. This reduces the tracking computer power requirements and keeps you from taking one of your own up the tailpipe.\par
\par
Striking a Roid with a bullet or, while not recommended, with your ship, results in the destruction of both and increases your score. Larger Roids are less challenging to strike and grant a smaller reward. Striking a Roid breaks it into two smaller Roids. Eventually a Roid becomes so small it is completely vaporized.\par
\par
When all the Roids are destroyed you'll be warped to the next sector. Upon disengaging the warp drive the ship experiences momentarily invulnerability. This effect quickly dissipates as the warp field collapses and the ship transitions back to normal space. During this time you should manuever the ship to a clear area to prevent a reentry collision. You'll notice each sector begins with more Roids than its predecessor. \par
\par
If a ship is destroyed and you have exhausted your supply of ships the game is over. Otherwise another ship will warp to the predecessor's location. \par
